File to edit: e2e/secret-rotation.e2e.ts (this file already tests POST /reload with the old secret during rotation, so adding auth enforcement tests here is a natural fit).

Alternatively, the tests could go in e2e/health-endpoint.e2e.ts alongside the existing 'GET /audit without Bearer auth returns 401' test (line 301), since it follows the same auth enforcement pattern.

The existing pattern to follow is in e2e/audit-logging.e2e.ts lines 296-304:
```typescript
test('GET /audit without Bearer auth returns 401', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
    await setupToolTest(mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient);
    const res = await fetch(`http://localhost:${mcpServer.port}/audit`, {
      signal: AbortSignal.timeout(5_000),
    });
    expect(res.status).toBe(401);
  });
```

The POST /reload tests should follow the same pattern but use method: 'POST':
1. POST /reload with no auth header → expect 401
2. POST /reload with wrong Bearer token → expect 401
3. POST /reload with correct Bearer token → expect 200 (this is already covered by existing tests but could be added as a positive control)

The simplest approach is to add these tests to e2e/secret-rotation.e2e.ts as a new describe block: 'POST /reload authentication'. These tests are server-only (no extension/browser needed), so they can use `startMcpServer` directly with createTestConfigDir/cleanupTestConfigDir, similar to the existing test in that file.
